1
00:00:19,520 --> 00:00:23,424
Hello and welcome to
a Grand Tour special,

2
00:00:23,491 --> 00:00:26,427
which begins with this:
the Volkswagen Beetle.

3
00:00:26,494 --> 00:00:28,462
It's a car we hate very much

4
00:00:28,529 --> 00:00:31,999
because it appeals only
to Nazis and hippies,

5
00:00:32,066 --> 00:00:35,069
and we are neither
of those things.

6
00:00:35,136 --> 00:00:37,538
However,
if you remove the bodywork

7
00:00:37,605 --> 00:00:40,007
and replace it with something
a bit more fun -

8
00:00:40,074 --> 00:00:41,275
something like this--

9
00:00:41,342 --> 00:00:43,377
you end up with
a beach buggy,

10
00:00:43,444 --> 00:00:45,346
and that's brilliant.

11
00:00:45,413 --> 00:00:47,415
We love beach buggies.

12
00:00:47,481 --> 00:00:49,850
However, Mr. Wilman disagrees.

13
00:00:49,917 --> 00:00:52,120
He says that
if they'd been any good,

14
00:00:52,186 --> 00:00:53,554
they would have caught on,

15
00:00:53,621 --> 00:00:56,023
and he points out
that they didn't.

16
00:00:56,090 --> 00:00:59,827
So he hatched a plan.
And it's this:

17
00:00:59,893 --> 00:01:03,397
he said all three of us
must buy a Volkswagen Beetle,

18
00:01:03,464 --> 00:01:05,633
turn it into a beach buggy,

19
00:01:05,699 --> 00:01:06,867
and then report with it

20
00:01:06,934 --> 00:01:11,172
to a wild, rugged
and extremely remote place--

21
00:01:11,239 --> 00:01:14,675
here on the coast of Namibia.

22
00:01:34,328 --> 00:01:36,364
(ENGINE RUMBLES)

23
00:01:36,430 --> 00:01:38,266
(SURF GUITAR MUSIC)

24
00:01:38,332 --> 00:01:40,168
This is what I've built.

25
00:01:41,602 --> 00:01:43,971
It's as close
as you can possibly get

26
00:01:44,037 --> 00:01:47,175
to the original
1964 beach buggy

27
00:01:47,208 --> 00:01:48,809
built by Bruce Meyers.

28
00:01:51,379 --> 00:01:55,549
Underneath,
it is a 1950s Beetle--

29
00:01:55,616 --> 00:01:57,451
Beetle floorpan,
Beetle suspension,

30
00:01:57,518 --> 00:01:59,253
Beetle engine,
Beetle gearbox.

31
00:01:59,320 --> 00:02:00,621
It's got Beetle lights on it.

32
00:02:00,688 --> 00:02:02,290
I've even got
a Beetle speedometer

33
00:02:02,356 --> 00:02:04,192
and Beetle hubcaps.

34
00:02:05,359 --> 00:02:07,195
It's brilliant!

35
00:02:10,664 --> 00:02:14,535
This is a beach buggy
very like the one
that Steve McQueen drove

36
00:02:14,602 --> 00:02:16,337
in the original
Thomas Crown Affair.

37
00:02:16,404 --> 00:02:18,406
- And if it's good enough--
- (HORN TOOTS)

38
00:02:18,472 --> 00:02:22,009
- Oh, God.
- Ha-ha!

39
00:02:22,075 --> 00:02:24,612
I've been joined
by the 1970s.

40
00:02:24,678 --> 00:02:26,814
♫ T.REX: "20th Century Boy"

41
00:02:28,982 --> 00:02:30,251
Yes.

42
00:02:30,318 --> 00:02:34,655
James May has built
what a beach buggy was,

43
00:02:34,722 --> 00:02:37,891
what I've built is what
a beach buggy can be...

44
00:02:40,828 --> 00:02:43,431
...if you have
a bit of imagination

45
00:02:43,497 --> 00:02:46,234
and some purple
metal-flake paint.

46
00:02:46,234 --> 00:02:48,035
Ha-ha-ha-ha!

47
00:02:48,101 --> 00:02:53,907
♫ Twentieth century toy,
I wanna be your boy... ♫

48
00:02:53,974 --> 00:02:57,411
There, I believe,
is the start point
of our adventure.

49
00:02:58,679 --> 00:03:01,749
♫ I wanna be your boy... ♫

50
00:03:04,418 --> 00:03:06,820
JEREMY:
What an extraordinary place.

51
00:03:06,887 --> 00:03:10,424
It's amazing, isn't it?
I mean, more seals.

52
00:03:10,491 --> 00:03:13,060
What David Attenborough
never told us about those

53
00:03:13,126 --> 00:03:15,996
is how bad they smell.

54
00:03:16,063 --> 00:03:20,401
JEREMY: Sadly, before
our nature documentary
could go any further,

55
00:03:20,468 --> 00:03:23,571
Richard Hammond
emerged from the mist.

56
00:03:23,637 --> 00:03:26,907
Ooh, hello.
That's not a beach buggy.

57
00:03:26,974 --> 00:03:29,943
- Is it?
- Well, I wouldn't
call that...

58
00:03:30,010 --> 00:03:32,313
- Ah-ha!
- Oh, geez.

59
00:03:32,380 --> 00:03:33,947
Ladies and gentlemen,
Dick-tari!

60
00:03:35,048 --> 00:03:36,284
RICHARD: Behold!

61
00:03:37,285 --> 00:03:38,486
JAMES: What are you wearing?

62
00:03:38,552 --> 00:03:40,288
What are you wearing?

63
00:03:40,288 --> 00:03:41,489
Well, I'm in Africa!

64
00:03:41,555 --> 00:03:43,023
- (JAMES LAUGHS)
- These trousers,

65
00:03:43,090 --> 00:03:44,458
did they say in the shop,

66
00:03:44,525 --> 00:03:46,093
"I'm afraid
they are yellow, sir"?

67
00:03:46,159 --> 00:03:47,495
When you left,
they went, "Yes!

68
00:03:47,561 --> 00:03:50,197
20 years we've had
those on the hanger!"

69
00:03:50,298 --> 00:03:51,565
- (THEY LAUGH)
- Shut up.

70
00:03:51,632 --> 00:03:53,066
And then we must
move over to this.

71
00:03:53,133 --> 00:03:54,902
- Yeah.
- We were told

72
00:03:54,968 --> 00:03:56,904
to build beach buggies.

73
00:03:56,970 --> 00:03:58,572
- Yes.
- Beach buggies.

74
00:03:58,639 --> 00:04:00,441
JAMES: It's not a beach buggy.
JEREMY: It isn't.

75
00:04:00,508 --> 00:04:01,842
RICHARD: It is a beach buggy.

76
00:04:01,909 --> 00:04:03,611
It isn't a beach buggy.
It's got a roof!

77
00:04:03,677 --> 00:04:05,346
There's no Beetle
in here at all.

78
00:04:05,413 --> 00:04:07,515
Yes, there is.
Beetle engine in there.

79
00:04:07,581 --> 00:04:10,551
OK, this space-frame chassis...

80
00:04:10,618 --> 00:04:12,185
- Yeah.
- Is it from a Beetle?

81
00:04:12,320 --> 00:04:15,323
- No.
- These enormous
suspension components

82
00:04:15,389 --> 00:04:17,224
that don't even fit
under the bodywork.

83
00:04:17,325 --> 00:04:20,761
- You've got two lots
of suspension at the back.
- Twin shocks.

84
00:04:20,828 --> 00:04:24,965
- Twin shocks?
- I like an off-road
sort of vibe.

85
00:04:25,032 --> 00:04:27,200
To get here,
we had to drive on a beach.

86
00:04:27,335 --> 00:04:28,802
-Yeah.
-Ours have made it.

87
00:04:28,869 --> 00:04:31,104
I didn't need two lots
of rear suspension on mine.

88
00:04:31,171 --> 00:04:32,373
Neither did I.

89
00:04:32,440 --> 00:04:34,207
Look, we were told
to come to Africa.

90
00:04:34,342 --> 00:04:38,979
If we'd been told to go
to Santa Monica Beach,
then this, with its...

91
00:04:39,046 --> 00:04:40,047
(JEREMY CLEARS HIS THROAT)

92
00:04:40,113 --> 00:04:41,815
...incredibly vivid paint...

93
00:04:41,882 --> 00:04:44,051
That's the most metal flake
I've ever seen.

94
00:04:44,117 --> 00:04:45,353
Any beach in the world.

95
00:04:45,386 --> 00:04:47,020
Um...

96
00:04:47,087 --> 00:04:49,690
- Hang on, what's that?
- That's the engine.

97
00:04:49,757 --> 00:04:52,225
- What engine is it?
- V8!

98
00:04:52,360 --> 00:04:53,961
I've put a V8
in a beach buggy!

99
00:04:54,027 --> 00:04:55,262
Well, no, you haven't.

100
00:04:55,363 --> 00:04:57,230
You've parked your
beach buggy quite close.

101
00:04:57,365 --> 00:04:58,566
It's not in it!

102
00:04:58,632 --> 00:04:59,933
- It isn't in it.
- (RICHARD LAUGHS) No.

103
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:01,068
You've reversed into a V8,

104
00:05:01,134 --> 00:05:02,436
but not quite hard enough.

105
00:05:02,503 --> 00:05:04,004
It's only gone in
a third of the way.

106
00:05:04,071 --> 00:05:05,773
Do you have any idea
how difficult it is

107
00:05:05,839 --> 00:05:07,808
to fit a V8 to a beach buggy?

108
00:05:07,875 --> 00:05:09,377
- Well, it doesn't fit!
- It's obviously impossible.

109
00:05:09,377 --> 00:05:10,978
Exactly, it's impossible.

110
00:05:11,044 --> 00:05:12,580
This is no ordinary V8.

111
00:05:12,646 --> 00:05:14,014
It started out in life

112
00:05:14,081 --> 00:05:16,149
as a 3.5 litre V8
from a Range Rover,

113
00:05:16,216 --> 00:05:21,288
but I've modified it,
so it produces
180 horsepower.

114
00:05:21,389 --> 00:05:23,256
Can I just say,
you were doubting

115
00:05:23,391 --> 00:05:25,092
the credibility of mine
as a beach buggy.

116
00:05:25,158 --> 00:05:26,494
Yeah.

117
00:05:26,560 --> 00:05:28,228
The defining characteristic
of a beach buggy

118
00:05:28,295 --> 00:05:30,831
is an air-cooled,
flat-four Beetle engine.

119
00:05:30,898 --> 00:05:31,832
(CLEARS THROAT)

120
00:05:31,899 --> 00:05:33,401
No, that's not
an engine, James.

121
00:05:33,401 --> 00:05:34,602
That's just a fan.

122
00:05:34,668 --> 00:05:36,103
How many horsepower
does yours have?

123
00:05:36,169 --> 00:05:37,405
94!

124
00:05:37,438 --> 00:05:39,306
So I have twice
as many horsepower.

125
00:05:39,407 --> 00:05:41,542
- Shall I tell you something?
- They're not in the car,
though.

126
00:05:41,609 --> 00:05:43,411
- They are, they're near it.
- Yes.

127
00:05:43,411 --> 00:05:45,746
It's interesting, isn't it?
I mean, that is an entire--

128
00:05:45,813 --> 00:05:47,080
Nothing about that
is interesting.

129
00:05:47,147 --> 00:05:48,416
This is a blank canvas

130
00:05:48,416 --> 00:05:49,483
onto which you could
paint your personality.

131
00:05:49,550 --> 00:05:51,118
- Yes.
- Yours has got

132
00:05:51,184 --> 00:05:52,886
a prolapsed V8 hanging
out of its backside

133
00:05:52,953 --> 00:05:54,121
and terrible paint.

134
00:05:54,187 --> 00:05:55,523
Mine is a rather magnificent

135
00:05:55,589 --> 00:05:56,890
"Daktari"-themed off-roader.

136
00:05:56,957 --> 00:05:59,292
(LAUGHS)
That's got nothing on it!

137
00:05:59,427 --> 00:06:01,028
- You can express...
- JEREMY: It is a bit boring.

138
00:06:01,094 --> 00:06:02,696
...all your personality,
and it's standard.

139
00:06:02,763 --> 00:06:04,264
It's not...
What do you mean, standard?

140
00:06:04,331 --> 00:06:05,433
It's a beach buggy.

141
00:06:05,499 --> 00:06:06,867
- It's tasteful.
- (BLEEPING)

142
00:06:06,934 --> 00:06:08,101
What?

143
00:06:09,437 --> 00:06:12,105
- Oh.
- The bat sat-phone.

144
00:06:12,172 --> 00:06:13,641
We've got a message from...

145
00:06:14,508 --> 00:06:15,509
Mr. Wilman.

146
00:06:15,576 --> 00:06:16,844
RICHARD: Right, go on.

147
00:06:16,910 --> 00:06:18,245
"Since you're in
beach buggies..."

148
00:06:18,311 --> 00:06:19,913
Well, us two are.

149
00:06:19,980 --> 00:06:21,882
"Since you're
in beach buggies,

150
00:06:21,949 --> 00:06:25,052
you will now
drive to the beach."

151
00:06:25,118 --> 00:06:26,186
Uh... (LAUGHS)

152
00:06:26,253 --> 00:06:27,354
Uh...do you think

153
00:06:27,455 --> 00:06:28,956
he's taken leave
of his senses?

154
00:06:29,022 --> 00:06:30,791
Well, he was never that good
at geography, was he?

155
00:06:30,858 --> 00:06:32,893
No, he wasn't. "You'll now
drive to the beach."

156
00:06:32,960 --> 00:06:34,294
Hold on.
Oh, no, there's more.

157
00:06:34,361 --> 00:06:36,096
"The beach
to which you will drive

158
00:06:36,163 --> 00:06:41,168
is located on
the crocodile-infested
Kunene River

159
00:06:41,234 --> 00:06:46,139
at the northernmost
point of Namibia,
where it meets Angola.

160
00:06:46,206 --> 00:06:48,175
It's 1,000 miles away."

161
00:06:49,677 --> 00:06:53,180
- 1,000 miles?
- 1,000.

162
00:06:53,246 --> 00:06:56,116
JEREMY: What we needed
at this point was a map,

163
00:06:56,183 --> 00:06:59,219
so we decided
to head north up the coast

164
00:06:59,286 --> 00:07:01,054
and find the nearest town.

165
00:07:01,121 --> 00:07:03,491
JEREMY:
Let the journey begin!

166
00:07:03,524 --> 00:07:05,493
(ENGINES REV)

167
00:07:07,895 --> 00:07:10,831
JEREMY: And what a journey
it would be in these cars,

168
00:07:10,898 --> 00:07:14,702
cars that were born
in interesting times.

169
00:07:16,504 --> 00:07:18,972
So, it's 1964,

170
00:07:19,039 --> 00:07:22,175
the word "teenager"
has started to appear

171
00:07:22,242 --> 00:07:23,644
in the world's dictionaries,

172
00:07:23,711 --> 00:07:26,547
people are listening
to new types of music,

173
00:07:26,614 --> 00:07:29,683
they're smoking
new types of stuff.

174
00:07:29,750 --> 00:07:33,954
And then, in California,
the beach buggy arrived!

175
00:07:34,021 --> 00:07:35,222
(ENGINES RUMBLE)

176
00:07:39,192 --> 00:07:40,594
It was perfect!

177
00:07:40,661 --> 00:07:43,330
Girls and boys,
beach barbecues...

178
00:07:43,396 --> 00:07:46,900
The first design criteria
was that the front fenders
were flat,

179
00:07:46,967 --> 00:07:49,202
so you could stand
a beer on it.

180
00:07:49,269 --> 00:07:51,038
That's how you design a car!

181
00:07:54,842 --> 00:07:59,547
Jimi Hendrix had a beach buggy
and President Nixon didn't.

182
00:07:59,580 --> 00:08:01,549
Tells you
all you need to know.

183
00:08:03,951 --> 00:08:07,354
What I really like
about the beach buggy
is that it's a testament

184
00:08:07,420 --> 00:08:10,991
to the ability of
the human spirit to triumph.

185
00:08:11,058 --> 00:08:12,960
Because somebody looked
at the Beetle and said,

186
00:08:13,026 --> 00:08:17,364
"Well, that's the legacy of
the world's worst dictator.

187
00:08:17,430 --> 00:08:19,266
Let's turn it
into a beach car."

188
00:08:23,003 --> 00:08:24,805
JEREMY: After a lonely hour

189
00:08:24,872 --> 00:08:27,007
of driving north
through the swirling mist,

190
00:08:27,074 --> 00:08:29,677
we still hadn't found a town,

191
00:08:29,743 --> 00:08:32,880
but we did find
something else.

192
00:08:34,181 --> 00:08:35,583
Jesus.

193
00:08:56,269 --> 00:08:57,605
JEREMY: I'll tell you what,

194
00:08:57,671 --> 00:08:59,439
he must have been
going at a right old lick

195
00:08:59,506 --> 00:09:00,608
when he hit the beach.

196
00:09:00,608 --> 00:09:01,809
RICHARD: He must have been.

197
00:09:01,875 --> 00:09:03,811
Right, the sea is there.

198
00:09:03,877 --> 00:09:05,445
That's half a mile away.

199
00:09:05,512 --> 00:09:06,513
JAMES: I'd say so.

200
00:09:06,614 --> 00:09:07,848
So he got it up the beach,

201
00:09:07,915 --> 00:09:09,382
and then sort of did
a handbrake turn.

202
00:09:09,449 --> 00:09:11,685
-Power-slided it in.
-How do you do a handbrake...

203
00:09:11,752 --> 00:09:14,054
RICHARD: How did it
get here, seriously?

204
00:09:14,121 --> 00:09:16,857
Can I just say...
my nipples are erect.

205
00:09:16,924 --> 00:09:19,226
- What, 'cause
of this jacket?
- No.

206
00:09:19,292 --> 00:09:20,628
- Oh.
- It's cold.

207
00:09:20,661 --> 00:09:23,063
- It is, isn't it?
- It's cold.

208
00:09:23,130 --> 00:09:25,432
That's an unwise
wardrobe strategy.

209
00:09:25,498 --> 00:09:26,667
Yeah, well, you know,

210
00:09:26,734 --> 00:09:28,936
Africa, on a beach,
I thought...

211
00:09:29,002 --> 00:09:30,771
- So did I.
- I'm surprised.

212
00:09:32,239 --> 00:09:35,308
The beach has got
the sea haar on it -

213
00:09:35,375 --> 00:09:37,144
mist, fog, cold.

214
00:09:37,210 --> 00:09:40,313
- If you look over there...
- Hm.

215
00:09:40,380 --> 00:09:42,015
...sunshine, blue sky.

216
00:09:42,082 --> 00:09:44,652
- Why don't we just
go inland...
- The coast road.

217
00:09:44,652 --> 00:09:47,354
Find the coast road
which will take us
to a town.

218
00:09:47,420 --> 00:09:49,723
And that'll be in the sun.
That's a better idea.

219
00:09:50,924 --> 00:09:52,325
JEREMY:
With a plan worked out,

220
00:09:52,392 --> 00:09:54,662
it was time
to get moving again.

221
00:09:54,695 --> 00:09:56,830
(ENGINE IGNITION FAILS)

222
00:09:58,766 --> 00:10:00,067
Oh, dear.

223
00:10:00,133 --> 00:10:02,169
JAMES: Did you modify
the battery as well?

224
00:10:02,235 --> 00:10:04,304
- (IGNITION FAILS)
- RICHARD: Oh...

225
00:10:04,371 --> 00:10:07,775
- It's obviously not
charging up.
- No.

226
00:10:07,841 --> 00:10:09,576
Because I didn't modify it.

227
00:10:09,643 --> 00:10:10,744
Yeah.

228
00:10:10,811 --> 00:10:12,512
I'll just see if mine works.

229
00:10:12,579 --> 00:10:14,047
(ENGINE STARTS)

230
00:10:14,114 --> 00:10:16,449
- Oh, yeah.
- Let me just try mine.

231
00:10:16,516 --> 00:10:18,752
- (ENGINE STARTS)
- Yeah.

232
00:10:18,819 --> 00:10:20,888
- Push?
- Hm?

233
00:10:20,954 --> 00:10:24,124
- Can I have a push?
- (ENGINES REV)

234
00:10:31,231 --> 00:10:33,967
JEREMY: After the film crew
had got me going,

235
00:10:34,034 --> 00:10:37,971
I used my massive horsepower
to catch the others.

236
00:10:44,277 --> 00:10:47,247
But by the time we were
back together again...

237
00:10:48,448 --> 00:10:50,383
it was going dark.

238
00:10:50,450 --> 00:10:54,187
The sun, as you can see
over my shoulder, has set,

239
00:10:54,254 --> 00:10:56,724
and we still
haven't found a road.

240
00:10:56,790 --> 00:11:00,093
It's also going to be very,
very, very cold.

241
00:11:01,762 --> 00:11:03,096
Lights on.

242
00:11:10,370 --> 00:11:12,439
RICHARD: We have
got to find this road.

243
00:11:13,907 --> 00:11:15,876
This is not going to be
too clever...

244
00:11:17,144 --> 00:11:18,411
in the dark.

245
00:11:24,918 --> 00:11:27,120
I've rather crudely
rigged up my torch,

246
00:11:27,187 --> 00:11:29,923
wedged in
the windscreen rail,

247
00:11:29,990 --> 00:11:33,994
in the hope that you can see
my last pieces to camera.

248
00:11:37,831 --> 00:11:39,466
Oh, bollocks!

249
00:11:42,302 --> 00:11:43,771
(INHALES SHARPLY)

250
00:11:43,837 --> 00:11:45,405
Oh, cold!

251
00:11:49,042 --> 00:11:50,377
JEREMY: Finally, though,

252
00:11:50,443 --> 00:11:53,680
it looked like
our luck had changed.

253
00:11:53,781 --> 00:11:55,648
Ooh, hello! Hello!

254
00:11:55,783 --> 00:11:57,117
What's that?

255
00:12:03,623 --> 00:12:05,325
- It's not a hotel.
- No.

256
00:12:07,795 --> 00:12:09,462
It smells of excrement!

257
00:12:09,529 --> 00:12:10,630
JAMES: Oh, wow, look at this!

258
00:12:10,697 --> 00:12:12,800
There's still, like, plates

259
00:12:12,800 --> 00:12:14,201
and cups and saucers
and things in here.

260
00:12:14,267 --> 00:12:15,869
I'll tell you exactly
what this is.

261
00:12:15,936 --> 00:12:17,304
It's an abandoned mine.

262
00:12:17,370 --> 00:12:18,405
(JEREMY SNIFFS)

263
00:12:18,471 --> 00:12:20,673
They do mine round
in Namibia, don't they?

264
00:12:20,808 --> 00:12:21,942
What do they mine for?

265
00:12:22,009 --> 00:12:23,543
- Diamonds.
- Diamonds?

266
00:12:23,610 --> 00:12:26,246
Yeah, but they wouldn't
have left if there were any.

267
00:12:26,313 --> 00:12:28,515
They obviously left,
and not yesterday.

268
00:12:31,218 --> 00:12:34,454
Look, there's no road here,
is there?

269
00:12:34,521 --> 00:12:35,488
- No.
- No.

270
00:12:35,555 --> 00:12:36,924
Apart from anything else,

271
00:12:36,990 --> 00:12:38,625
we can't find our way
around in the dark

272
00:12:38,691 --> 00:12:39,726
'cause we can't navigate.

273
00:12:39,827 --> 00:12:41,328
- Well, I can.
- How?

274
00:12:41,394 --> 00:12:42,963
- How?
- Stars.

275
00:12:43,030 --> 00:12:44,397
- No, you can't.
- I can.

276
00:12:44,464 --> 00:12:47,835
I can't do very many
things, I admit...

277
00:12:47,835 --> 00:12:49,837
...anything,
but I can do that.

278
00:12:49,903 --> 00:12:51,571
How do you navigate
by the stars?

279
00:12:51,638 --> 00:12:52,973
Uh...
find the Southern Cross.

280
00:12:53,040 --> 00:12:54,574
Yeah, but that's
really complicated.

281
00:12:54,641 --> 00:12:57,277
Right, do you want to sleep
in the excrement mine?

282
00:12:57,344 --> 00:12:58,645
No, this is out.

283
00:12:58,711 --> 00:13:00,380
So, we have to keep going,

284
00:13:00,447 --> 00:13:02,615
whether we like it or not,
till we find...

285
00:13:02,682 --> 00:13:04,251
We have to, so listen.

286
00:13:04,317 --> 00:13:06,753
I shall find
the Southern Cross.

287
00:13:06,854 --> 00:13:09,089
You can't find
the Southern Cross
with a hammer.

288
00:13:09,156 --> 00:13:11,959
I've found it!
Ha! I've found it.
It's there.

289
00:13:12,025 --> 00:13:13,560
It's like a kite.

290
00:13:13,626 --> 00:13:14,995
- That one there?
- Yeah.

291
00:13:15,062 --> 00:13:16,864
It's a kite shape.
It's sort of...

292
00:13:16,930 --> 00:13:20,733
Now, you take
the long axis, yes?

293
00:13:20,868 --> 00:13:21,869
- Yes.
- Mm-hm.

294
00:13:21,902 --> 00:13:24,004
And draw an imaginary line

295
00:13:24,071 --> 00:13:27,474
through it,
down to the horizon.

296
00:13:27,540 --> 00:13:29,076
Yes? Now, you intersect it

297
00:13:29,142 --> 00:13:32,212
from a line drawn
between two other stars,

298
00:13:32,279 --> 00:13:35,048
and where those
two imaginary lines meet,

299
00:13:35,115 --> 00:13:38,618
directly underneath it
is due south.

300
00:13:38,685 --> 00:13:40,653
So if it's those two--

301
00:13:40,720 --> 00:13:42,455
which it is, I'm sure of it--

302
00:13:42,522 --> 00:13:44,491
you draw a line...

303
00:13:44,557 --> 00:13:46,493
(ENGINE RUMBLES)

304
00:13:49,796 --> 00:13:52,399
Oh, this is a bad idea!

305
00:13:52,465 --> 00:13:55,135
We are now trusting
our lives to an orangutan

306
00:13:55,202 --> 00:13:57,004
who thinks
he's Patrick Moore.

307
00:13:59,339 --> 00:14:02,609
There it is.
There's the two stars.

308
00:14:03,911 --> 00:14:06,713
Draw a line...

309
00:14:06,779 --> 00:14:10,183
I'm not getting many
directions from you, Jeremy.
Is this right?

310
00:14:10,250 --> 00:14:12,920
You're heading a little bit
too much to the right.

311
00:14:12,986 --> 00:14:15,022
You need to go left a bit.

312
00:14:15,088 --> 00:14:17,991
Good, good.
Oh, I'm so confident.

313
00:14:18,058 --> 00:14:23,296
You two are going to be
eating humble pie
when the sun comes up.

314
00:14:27,167 --> 00:14:28,835
RICHARD: Despite
the confidence

315
00:14:28,936 --> 00:14:30,603
of Jeremy Columbus,

316
00:14:30,670 --> 00:14:33,040
no road appeared.

317
00:14:34,674 --> 00:14:36,076
Oh, this is grim.

318
00:14:40,047 --> 00:14:42,315
Excuse me.

319
00:14:42,382 --> 00:14:45,418
I've been on the go
a very, very long time now.

320
00:14:47,654 --> 00:14:52,125
RICHARD: Guys, I'm sorry.
I'm not driving another inch.

321
00:14:52,192 --> 00:14:53,994
I can't do this.

322
00:14:54,061 --> 00:14:55,495
It's three o'clock
in the morning.

323
00:14:55,562 --> 00:14:56,964
I'm exhausted.

324
00:14:56,964 --> 00:14:59,466
JEREMY: He does have a point.

325
00:15:05,838 --> 00:15:07,340
RICHARD: The next morning,

326
00:15:07,407 --> 00:15:10,043
we woke, having
slept on the sand,

327
00:15:10,110 --> 00:15:12,645
huddled round our engines
for warmth.

328
00:15:16,984 --> 00:15:19,052
(ENGINE STARTS)

329
00:15:29,129 --> 00:15:31,464
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

330
00:15:34,101 --> 00:15:35,668
(HORN TOOTS)

331
00:15:41,141 --> 00:15:43,310
JAMES:
You muppet. What's that?

332
00:15:43,376 --> 00:15:44,377
Um...

333
00:15:45,712 --> 00:15:48,015
"Um" what?

334
00:15:48,048 --> 00:15:51,084
I never knew
Namibia had two seas.

335
00:15:51,151 --> 00:15:52,519
It doesn't have two seas.

336
00:15:52,585 --> 00:15:54,187
No, it has one
massive "cee" in it.

337
00:15:54,254 --> 00:15:55,655
One massive, stupid "cee"

338
00:15:55,722 --> 00:15:57,657
that's navigated us back
to where we started.

339
00:15:57,724 --> 00:15:59,726
- Can I just say...
- It wasn't my... I...

340
00:15:59,792 --> 00:16:02,029
Why did we even believe
you could navigate
by the stars?

341
00:16:02,095 --> 00:16:03,430
You can't even
read a compass.

342
00:16:03,496 --> 00:16:06,099
There are two "cees".
There's two "cees" here

343
00:16:06,166 --> 00:16:08,268
for believing that
that "cee" could navigate us.

344
00:16:08,335 --> 00:16:10,370
- No, you're right.
- I couldn't possibly...

345
00:16:10,437 --> 00:16:12,872
Really,
I don't understand that.

346
00:16:12,939 --> 00:16:15,775
JAMES: Freezing cold,
sandpapered on the face...

347
00:16:15,842 --> 00:16:18,278
- You've got a coat on.
- It's thin. Have you felt it?

348
00:16:18,345 --> 00:16:20,180
I haven't even got
a thin coat.

349
00:16:20,247 --> 00:16:21,581
I've only got
a T-shirt. Anyway,

350
00:16:21,648 --> 00:16:23,150
I'm not going to be
competitive with you

351
00:16:23,216 --> 00:16:24,551
about who's the coldest.

352
00:16:24,617 --> 00:16:26,453
- I'm the coldest!
- We're all the lostest.

353
00:16:26,519 --> 00:16:28,821
Never mind. Look,
let's not get bogged down

354
00:16:28,888 --> 00:16:30,223
with whose fault it was.

355
00:16:30,290 --> 00:16:32,159
There's no being bogged
down with it, is there?

356
00:16:32,225 --> 00:16:34,127
It was yours.

357
00:16:34,194 --> 00:16:35,962
We can either go
back into the desert

358
00:16:36,063 --> 00:16:37,564
to look for a road,

359
00:16:37,630 --> 00:16:39,966
or we can just do what
we were doing yesterday,

360
00:16:40,067 --> 00:16:41,534
and stay on the beach.

361
00:16:41,601 --> 00:16:43,970
At least we know, if we
keep the sea on our left,

362
00:16:44,071 --> 00:16:45,238
we're going north.

363
00:16:45,305 --> 00:16:46,673
- Yes.
- That's a fair point.

364
00:16:46,739 --> 00:16:49,242
- Let's navigate by the sea.
- JEREMY: Yes.

365
00:16:50,543 --> 00:16:53,113
JEREMY: With our new--
well, newish--

366
00:16:53,180 --> 00:16:54,314
plan in place,

367
00:16:54,381 --> 00:16:56,183
we set off once more.

368
00:16:57,784 --> 00:17:01,754
So here we are. These are our
wheel marks from yesterday.

369
00:17:02,955 --> 00:17:06,393
24 hours of cold, misery...

370
00:17:06,459 --> 00:17:08,428
to achieve exactly nothing.

371
00:17:08,495 --> 00:17:11,131
I mean,
it is exactly nothing.

372
00:17:11,198 --> 00:17:14,501
But, apart from that
and the weather...

373
00:17:14,567 --> 00:17:19,406
and Jeremy Clarkson,
it's all going really well.

374
00:17:19,472 --> 00:17:21,274
JEREMY:
As we continued north,

375
00:17:21,341 --> 00:17:23,776
the misery of
the previous day was banished

376
00:17:23,843 --> 00:17:27,580
by the sheer bigness
of our surroundings.

377
00:17:27,647 --> 00:17:30,583
Oh, this is
an astonishing place.

378
00:17:33,553 --> 00:17:37,457
I've got a dune the size
of Mount Everest to my right,

379
00:17:37,524 --> 00:17:40,727
the Atlantic Ocean
to my left...

380
00:17:40,793 --> 00:17:41,861
(LAUGHS)

381
00:17:41,928 --> 00:17:44,697
This is absolutely epic.

382
00:17:53,306 --> 00:17:55,142
This is proper
beach buggy driving.

383
00:17:55,208 --> 00:17:58,611
Sun's out, sea's there
with the surf.

384
00:17:58,678 --> 00:18:00,580
It's like being
in the Beach Boys.

385
00:18:03,150 --> 00:18:05,352
(LAUGHS)

386
00:18:05,418 --> 00:18:07,554
JEREMY: Amidst all
this loveliness, though,

387
00:18:07,620 --> 00:18:12,825
there was one small elephant
edging its way into the room.

388
00:18:12,892 --> 00:18:14,727
Chaps, I don't want to
have to say this,

389
00:18:14,794 --> 00:18:18,231
but is the tide coming in
or going out?

390
00:18:20,167 --> 00:18:22,702
RICHARD:
Uh...I'm guessing in.

391
00:18:24,804 --> 00:18:27,307
There's no way
up the sides of that.

392
00:18:28,541 --> 00:18:32,011
And if the tide comes in
that far, which it does,

393
00:18:32,078 --> 00:18:34,181
we've had it.

394
00:18:34,247 --> 00:18:35,815
Got to keep moving here.

395
00:18:35,882 --> 00:18:37,517
We cannot afford
to get stuck.

396
00:18:41,754 --> 00:18:44,191
JEREMY: With some generous
use of the throttle,

397
00:18:44,191 --> 00:18:45,625
we managed to get clear

398
00:18:45,692 --> 00:18:48,595
of the sea-and-sand-dune
pincer movement.

399
00:18:48,661 --> 00:18:51,631
But then we had
another problem.

400
00:18:54,601 --> 00:18:56,703
I'd say that was the end
of the beach.

401
00:18:57,937 --> 00:18:59,772
RICHARD: How does that
just end like that?

402
00:18:59,839 --> 00:19:01,708
JEREMY: It does just end.
JAMES: That is the end.

403
00:19:01,774 --> 00:19:04,043
JEREMY: And the Namibian
government doesn't allow us

404
00:19:04,110 --> 00:19:06,679
to drive on the salt pans,
and that's what that is.

405
00:19:06,746 --> 00:19:08,315
This meant,
according to James,

406
00:19:08,381 --> 00:19:11,684
we had only one option.

407
00:19:11,751 --> 00:19:13,553
We've got to go back
the way we came.

408
00:19:13,620 --> 00:19:14,987
But if the tide's coming in,

409
00:19:15,054 --> 00:19:18,325
that narrow bit
will have become impassable.

410
00:19:18,391 --> 00:19:22,028
That's why I think
if we see a good opportunity
to turn left,

411
00:19:22,094 --> 00:19:24,364
like we did last night,
we do it.

412
00:19:24,431 --> 00:19:26,399
Are you honestly suggesting
we go back in the...

413
00:19:26,466 --> 00:19:28,235
Well, where else can we go?

414
00:19:28,235 --> 00:19:30,337
We'll either drown
or starve otherwise.

415
00:19:36,243 --> 00:19:37,677
Right, we've just
got to find a bit

416
00:19:37,744 --> 00:19:41,748
where we can get inland
before the tide comes in.

417
00:19:47,287 --> 00:19:49,822
That is getting closer
to that,

418
00:19:49,889 --> 00:19:51,624
and when that happens,
we've had it.

419
00:19:56,263 --> 00:19:57,964
RICHARD:
But as we thundered along,

420
00:19:58,030 --> 00:20:01,468
the dunes refused
to open up and let us in.

421
00:20:03,135 --> 00:20:04,504
That's the sea!

422
00:20:05,405 --> 00:20:07,274
It's the sea, there!

423
00:20:08,975 --> 00:20:10,510
Oh, it's coming at me!

424
00:20:12,211 --> 00:20:15,582
JEREMY: I still say
we can't get out here, look.

425
00:20:15,648 --> 00:20:17,550
No left turn at the moment.

426
00:20:21,454 --> 00:20:23,723
This is where you need a V8!

427
00:20:23,790 --> 00:20:24,991
(ENGINE REVS)

428
00:20:27,193 --> 00:20:28,395
Oh, shit.

429
00:20:29,829 --> 00:20:32,332
Oh, Jeremy's in trouble!

430
00:20:32,399 --> 00:20:34,100
That is not looking good!

431
00:20:34,166 --> 00:20:35,368
(ENGINE REVS)

432
00:20:35,435 --> 00:20:37,103
Come on, come on. Whoa.

433
00:20:37,169 --> 00:20:38,871
(ENGINE REVS)

434
00:20:38,938 --> 00:20:40,707
Oh, no.

435
00:20:40,773 --> 00:20:42,842
(ENGINE REVS)

436
00:20:42,909 --> 00:20:45,645
Oh, no. No, no, no.
Not a good place.

437
00:20:45,712 --> 00:20:48,114
- (ENGINE REVS)
- Oh, God.

438
00:20:48,180 --> 00:20:49,816
Uh...I'm in the sea.

439
00:20:51,384 --> 00:20:53,453
Because it was
a bit of an emergency,

440
00:20:53,520 --> 00:20:56,255
my colleagues
decided to help for once.

441
00:20:56,323 --> 00:20:59,058
- Go.
- (ENGINE WHIRRS)

442
00:20:59,125 --> 00:21:00,192
JAMES: No.

443
00:21:00,259 --> 00:21:01,894
Is that just spinning?

444
00:21:01,961 --> 00:21:03,530
It's beached under there.

445
00:21:03,596 --> 00:21:05,498
I don't see why
I can't push him with that.

446
00:21:05,565 --> 00:21:07,800
-All right, then. Try.
-All right.

447
00:21:07,867 --> 00:21:09,569
James, count us in.

448
00:21:09,636 --> 00:21:12,038
Three, two, one, away!

449
00:21:17,644 --> 00:21:20,347
JEREMY: Yes!
RICHARD: Right, let's go!

450
00:21:22,349 --> 00:21:27,086
Me getting beached cost us
time we never had
in the first place,

451
00:21:27,153 --> 00:21:29,422
and we were still trapped.

452
00:21:32,825 --> 00:21:34,060
Jesus Christ.

453
00:21:36,128 --> 00:21:37,830
Ah, it's coming in.

454
00:21:41,501 --> 00:21:43,670
Come on, come on, come on.

455
00:21:45,204 --> 00:21:46,506
Come on.

456
00:21:48,040 --> 00:21:49,075
Whoa!

457
00:21:54,381 --> 00:21:55,615
Oh!

458
00:21:57,249 --> 00:21:58,518
Oh, that's bad.

459
00:22:02,188 --> 00:22:03,222
Shit.

460
00:22:03,289 --> 00:22:04,724
(ENGINE REVS)

461
00:22:05,925 --> 00:22:06,993
Whoa!

462
00:22:09,629 --> 00:22:11,097
Come on, baby, come on.

463
00:22:13,400 --> 00:22:17,504
RICHARD:
Mercifully, the dunes finally
started to fall away

464
00:22:17,570 --> 00:22:19,572
and we were saved.

465
00:22:22,509 --> 00:22:25,512
-And we're through!
-We are, we are.

466
00:22:25,578 --> 00:22:26,879
That's a relief.

467
00:22:29,516 --> 00:22:31,083
So nearly got stuck then.

468
00:22:34,687 --> 00:22:37,657
RICHARD: We'd now been
on the go for 36 hours,

469
00:22:37,724 --> 00:22:42,662
and we were
pretty much back where
we started from... again.

470
00:22:42,729 --> 00:22:45,665
We were also soaked,
frozen, worn out,

471
00:22:45,732 --> 00:22:47,667
and because
we had no food with us,

472
00:22:47,734 --> 00:22:49,802
we were also hungry.

473
00:22:49,869 --> 00:22:53,706
But then Bear Clarkson
came to the rescue.

474
00:22:53,773 --> 00:22:57,243
Cold you go and get
some driftwood for a fire?

475
00:22:57,309 --> 00:23:01,180
And could you fashion
a rudimentary barbecue
grill of some sort?

476
00:23:01,247 --> 00:23:03,716
OK. Where did you get
the fishing rod from?

477
00:23:03,783 --> 00:23:05,885
It's my whip aerial.
It's a beach buggy.

478
00:23:05,952 --> 00:23:08,154
- I thought of that.
- They're fishing rods.

479
00:23:15,795 --> 00:23:18,598
This is going to make
a perfect little
fish grill thing, look.

480
00:23:23,603 --> 00:23:25,137
Have you got a fire lit yet?

481
00:23:25,204 --> 00:23:26,473
I thought you were fishing.

482
00:23:26,473 --> 00:23:28,741
I am fishing.
My car's fishing.

483
00:23:28,808 --> 00:23:30,843
- Look.
- Well, is it?

484
00:23:30,910 --> 00:23:33,079
- Yeah, look,
I've got the rods attached.
- It's parked.

485
00:23:33,145 --> 00:23:35,014
JEREMY: What's that?
JAMES: That's the grill.

486
00:23:35,081 --> 00:23:37,650
So we hold that
with the pliers
from my multi-tool,

487
00:23:37,717 --> 00:23:39,652
cut the fish up, fillet it...

488
00:23:39,719 --> 00:23:43,556
Can you do that?
There's no point asking him.
He can open a tin...

489
00:23:43,623 --> 00:23:45,024
Can you fillet a fish?

490
00:23:45,091 --> 00:23:47,159
- What, is it only fish?
- Well, it's the sea!

491
00:23:47,226 --> 00:23:49,829
What did you think I was
going to catch, a chicken?

492
00:23:49,896 --> 00:23:51,063
Oh, my God!

493
00:23:56,268 --> 00:23:59,506
RICHARD: Oh, my God!
JAMES: No, wait. Yes!

494
00:23:59,506 --> 00:24:01,708
Ha-ha-ha-ha!

495
00:24:01,774 --> 00:24:04,043
While Hammond went off
to get more driftwood,

496
00:24:04,110 --> 00:24:07,614
James and I set about
gutting the catch.

497
00:24:07,680 --> 00:24:11,283
JEREMY: Use his car
as the table. There we go.

498
00:24:11,350 --> 00:24:14,420
- That's his gut.
Look. You've got it.
- Yeah, right.

499
00:24:14,521 --> 00:24:16,022
Oh, God. Shit. Look,

500
00:24:16,088 --> 00:24:17,857
it's all gone literally
onto his exhaust.

501
00:24:17,924 --> 00:24:20,359
Oh, no. Never mind.
Look, I need your help.

502
00:24:20,426 --> 00:24:21,794
Right, saw its head off.

503
00:24:23,730 --> 00:24:26,866
- Ah, there we go.
- Excellent.

504
00:24:26,933 --> 00:24:29,135
- I think, but I'm not sure--
- It's gone under his seat.

505
00:24:29,201 --> 00:24:30,436
Oh, no. Has it?

506
00:24:30,537 --> 00:24:32,071
It's all right,
I'll get it out later.

507
00:24:36,175 --> 00:24:38,177
JAMES:
Oh, it's done a treat, this.

508
00:24:38,244 --> 00:24:39,879
Look at this, Hammond.

509
00:24:42,248 --> 00:24:44,450
Mm.

510
00:24:44,551 --> 00:24:45,885
Oh, that's all right,
isn't it?

511
00:24:48,020 --> 00:24:49,155
Ooh.

512
00:24:54,727 --> 00:24:56,563
It tastes like fish,
doesn't it?

513
00:24:57,730 --> 00:24:59,832
OK, does anybody want a beer?

514
00:25:01,033 --> 00:25:02,401
- JAMES: Have you got some?
- No.

515
00:25:02,468 --> 00:25:04,971
- Oh, you...
- (JEREMY LAUGHS)

516
00:25:05,037 --> 00:25:07,640
- That deserves a stabbing.
- (THEY LAUGH)

517
00:25:07,707 --> 00:25:08,775
That is a proper stabbing.

518
00:25:08,841 --> 00:25:10,109
That's properly out of order.

519
00:25:13,846 --> 00:25:15,181
RICHARD: After lunch,

520
00:25:15,247 --> 00:25:17,850
we set off once more
into the dunes.

521
00:25:20,152 --> 00:25:22,822
Right,
so let's keep heading east.

522
00:25:22,889 --> 00:25:25,825
And we must come to
a road at some...

523
00:25:25,892 --> 00:25:28,628
There has to be a road.

524
00:25:28,695 --> 00:25:31,598
JEREMY: But,
for mile after mile,

525
00:25:31,598 --> 00:25:32,899
there wasn't.

526
00:25:44,510 --> 00:25:46,045
It's the Namib Desert.

527
00:25:46,112 --> 00:25:50,983
"Namib" in the local dialect
means "big nothing".

528
00:25:56,155 --> 00:26:00,259
It must be the prettiest
desert in the world.

529
00:26:00,326 --> 00:26:02,094
It's just a sea of dunes.

530
00:26:07,299 --> 00:26:10,369
JEREMY: Dunes which
were getting bigger.

531
00:26:10,436 --> 00:26:13,973
JAMES: Bloody Nora,
look at the size of that!

532
00:26:15,942 --> 00:26:20,279
Engaging 180 horsepower.

533
00:26:20,346 --> 00:26:23,382
JEREMY: Climbing them in our
two-wheel-drive beach buggies

534
00:26:23,449 --> 00:26:25,084
was becoming tricky.

535
00:26:26,986 --> 00:26:32,191
Come on, you can do this.
You can do this!

536
00:26:32,258 --> 00:26:37,296
But by deploying the V8,
I was sort of all right.

537
00:26:37,363 --> 00:26:38,464
Yes!

538
00:26:38,530 --> 00:26:41,367
Oh-ho-ho-ho!

539
00:26:41,433 --> 00:26:45,571
Hammond had grippy tyres,
so he was all right, too.

540
00:26:45,672 --> 00:26:48,240
Please, make it. Please.

541
00:26:48,307 --> 00:26:49,575
(ENGINE REVS)

542
00:26:49,676 --> 00:26:50,910
Please!

543
00:26:53,045 --> 00:26:54,380
Ho-ho!

544
00:26:54,446 --> 00:26:55,948
There you go!

545
00:26:56,015 --> 00:26:58,985
However, back in the 1960s...

546
00:27:01,754 --> 00:27:03,990
Come on, little car.

547
00:27:04,056 --> 00:27:06,425
- (ENGINE SPLUTTERS)
- Oh, no, no, no.

548
00:27:06,492 --> 00:27:07,559
No, no.

549
00:27:07,694 --> 00:27:09,328
(ENGINE REVS)

550
00:27:12,164 --> 00:27:13,700
(ENGINE REVS)

551
00:27:19,171 --> 00:27:20,406
- Stuck?
- Yes.

552
00:27:20,472 --> 00:27:22,108
Two problems. Number one,

553
00:27:22,174 --> 00:27:24,711
he's put a 90 horsepower
engine in it,

554
00:27:24,711 --> 00:27:26,445
which actually
is probably only 40.

555
00:27:26,512 --> 00:27:27,847
- Yeah.
- And number two,

556
00:27:27,914 --> 00:27:30,717
he will not use
full power ever.

557
00:27:30,750 --> 00:27:34,320
Well, he's got
a 90 horsepower engine,
but a 5 horsepower foot.

558
00:27:34,386 --> 00:27:36,088
(JEREMY LAUGHS)

559
00:27:36,155 --> 00:27:39,125
And I bet you any money he's
saying "I had a misfire."

560
00:27:39,191 --> 00:27:40,226
(LAUGHS)

561
00:27:46,999 --> 00:27:48,835
You've got to push the
accelerator all the way to--

562
00:27:48,901 --> 00:27:50,136
I know, but... I know that.

563
00:27:50,202 --> 00:27:52,338
It occasionally has
a little misfire moment,

564
00:27:52,404 --> 00:27:53,572
and then I lose it.

565
00:27:53,639 --> 00:27:55,407
- (THEY LAUGH)
- He said it!

566
00:27:57,844 --> 00:28:00,346
JEREMY: And so
the afternoon continued.

567
00:28:00,412 --> 00:28:04,550
The Grunt Machine
and the Grit Machine
would forge ahead...

568
00:28:04,616 --> 00:28:08,454
There is no way in hell
I'm doing this!

569
00:28:08,520 --> 00:28:10,156
Yes!

570
00:28:13,659 --> 00:28:15,561
You star!

571
00:28:15,627 --> 00:28:16,929
...and then there'd be

572
00:28:16,996 --> 00:28:19,799
the inevitable
radio exchange.

573
00:28:19,866 --> 00:28:21,834
We appear to be a man down,
Jeremy.

574
00:28:21,901 --> 00:28:24,403
JEREMY:
James May, where are you?

575
00:28:24,470 --> 00:28:25,872
(ENGINE REVS)

576
00:28:29,408 --> 00:28:31,410
JEREMY: Because
we spent so much time

577
00:28:31,477 --> 00:28:34,046
waiting
for Captain Misfire,

578
00:28:34,113 --> 00:28:37,216
we were still in the desert
as dusk fell.

579
00:28:37,283 --> 00:28:41,320
And failing light meant it
was hard to spot obstacles.

580
00:28:42,922 --> 00:28:44,623
Right, sit rep.

581
00:28:44,690 --> 00:28:48,027
Jesus (BLEEP) Christ!

582
00:28:48,094 --> 00:28:50,797
- (RICHARD LAUGHS)
- Holy...

583
00:28:50,863 --> 00:28:53,199
(CONTINUES LAUGHING)

584
00:28:53,265 --> 00:28:55,701
- (BLEEP)
- Oh, my God!

585
00:28:55,802 --> 00:28:58,437
- (RICHARD LAUGHS)
- Oh, shit!

586
00:28:58,504 --> 00:29:00,439
RICHARD: Look at it!

587
00:29:00,506 --> 00:29:02,441
Mate, I've got
to have a look.

588
00:29:05,411 --> 00:29:08,214
Oh, shitty death...

589
00:29:10,116 --> 00:29:13,019
- I locked up.
That was just...
- Look, he's buried!

590
00:29:13,085 --> 00:29:16,688
- You've buried the front.
- I was completely locked up.

591
00:29:16,823 --> 00:29:18,257
'Cause I would have
gone down that.

592
00:29:18,324 --> 00:29:19,826
- (RICHARD LAUGHS)
- Look at it!

593
00:29:19,892 --> 00:29:22,361
(RICHARD EXCLAIMS)

594
00:29:22,428 --> 00:29:25,364
My close shave was a reminder
that, after dark,

595
00:29:25,431 --> 00:29:29,168
these dunes would become
very, very dangerous.

596
00:29:34,540 --> 00:29:37,643
RICHARD: It's getting
harder and harder
to read the terrain now.

597
00:29:37,709 --> 00:29:39,278
Is that a drop?
Is that a hill?

598
00:29:39,345 --> 00:29:41,848
Is that going up?
Is that a cliff?
What is it?

599
00:29:43,983 --> 00:29:46,018
Peril... peril.

600
00:29:47,453 --> 00:29:48,988
Oh, shit!

601
00:29:49,055 --> 00:29:50,957
Oh, I think there's
a drop off there.

602
00:29:51,991 --> 00:29:53,759
It's just a black abyss.

603
00:29:53,860 --> 00:29:57,096
That could be
a huge cliff again.

604
00:29:59,999 --> 00:30:02,268
RICHARD: Eventually,
we could take no more,

605
00:30:02,334 --> 00:30:07,273
and we had to settle down
for a second night
around our engines.

606
00:30:07,339 --> 00:30:08,507
(SIGHS)

607
00:30:30,562 --> 00:30:33,699
We will find a road.
There must...

608
00:30:33,765 --> 00:30:36,502
- It can't... It can't
go on forever, can it?
- No.

609
00:30:36,568 --> 00:30:40,472
It has to... There will be
a town, a road... something.

610
00:30:42,942 --> 00:30:46,112
RICHARD: Unfortunately,
to find salvation,

611
00:30:46,178 --> 00:30:50,249
we still had to climb
more dunes.

612
00:30:50,316 --> 00:30:53,953
Climb them and then
get down the other side.

613
00:30:54,020 --> 00:30:55,421
Oh, my God!

614
00:30:57,656 --> 00:30:59,191
Well, that's just a cliff!

615
00:31:01,060 --> 00:31:03,329
Whoa! Aargh!

616
00:31:07,366 --> 00:31:08,968
(GRUNTS)

617
00:31:10,002 --> 00:31:13,105
Whoa, this is a monster.

618
00:31:13,172 --> 00:31:16,675
Oh! (BLEEP)
I don't think I can do...!

619
00:31:16,742 --> 00:31:19,378
Whoa-ho-ho-ho!

620
00:31:24,450 --> 00:31:28,087
Whoa-a-a-a-a-a!

621
00:31:31,057 --> 00:31:32,324
Here we go.

622
00:31:32,391 --> 00:31:35,127
All three of us
simultaneously...

623
00:31:38,965 --> 00:31:40,399
Holy shit.

624
00:31:40,466 --> 00:31:43,069
Oh-h-h-h, shit!

625
00:31:43,135 --> 00:31:46,438
Argh-hhh! Ha-ha!

626
00:31:46,505 --> 00:31:49,408
Whoa-a-a-a-a!

627
00:31:51,010 --> 00:31:52,344
I wasn't scared.

628
00:31:56,782 --> 00:31:58,217
Oh, my God.

629
00:31:58,284 --> 00:32:01,687
Guys, this is the biggest yet
by a country mile.

630
00:32:03,689 --> 00:32:06,993
Whoa-a-a-a-a-a!

631
00:32:06,993 --> 00:32:08,460
Is that the size of the drop

632
00:32:08,527 --> 00:32:10,396
or what's happened
to his penis?

633
00:32:10,462 --> 00:32:13,265
(LAUGHTER)

634
00:32:13,332 --> 00:32:15,601
Right, then. Let's see
what all the fuss is about.

635
00:32:15,667 --> 00:32:17,636
Holy shit!

636
00:32:21,073 --> 00:32:26,012
Oh-h-h-h-h!

637
00:32:28,880 --> 00:32:30,249
Phwoar.

638
00:32:30,316 --> 00:32:32,018
And now straighten
those wheels, Richard,

639
00:32:32,051 --> 00:32:33,385
straighten them,

640
00:32:33,452 --> 00:32:35,021
because you've got to
go down straight.

641
00:32:35,087 --> 00:32:39,158
Holy shit.
Oh-h-h-h-h, shit!

642
00:32:39,225 --> 00:32:41,027
That is frightening.

643
00:32:46,798 --> 00:32:48,834
Love this desert.

644
00:32:48,900 --> 00:32:50,902
I'm never, ever, ever happier

645
00:32:51,037 --> 00:32:53,405
than I am
when I'm in a desert.

646
00:32:53,472 --> 00:32:57,609
And this... this is the best
desert I've ever been to.

647
00:33:00,246 --> 00:33:02,348
You can never really lose
sight of the fact, though,

648
00:33:02,414 --> 00:33:04,050
that what it actually is

649
00:33:04,116 --> 00:33:08,487
is a big, orange
killing engine.

650
00:33:08,554 --> 00:33:12,091
Now, a big crest's coming up.
No idea.

651
00:33:12,158 --> 00:33:15,761
Gentle rolling hill
or massive cliff?

652
00:33:15,827 --> 00:33:17,663
I don't know, Hammond!

653
00:33:17,729 --> 00:33:19,931
Hammond, seriously.

654
00:33:20,066 --> 00:33:21,833
Shit, he's gone.

655
00:33:21,900 --> 00:33:24,370
Hammond's gone, everyone.
Hammond's gone. Big one.

656
00:33:26,072 --> 00:33:27,406
(SIGHS)

657
00:33:28,640 --> 00:33:30,076
Oh, (BLEEP) me.

658
00:33:36,815 --> 00:33:40,286
How the (BLEEP)
did you get down that?

659
00:33:41,720 --> 00:33:44,090
With my eyes shut!

660
00:33:44,123 --> 00:33:46,492
(LAUGHS) That was terrifying!

661
00:33:46,558 --> 00:33:48,727
(LAUGHS)

662
00:33:48,794 --> 00:33:51,097
Jesus!

663
00:33:59,205 --> 00:34:01,140
JEREMY: As we
continued to head east,

664
00:34:01,207 --> 00:34:03,509
the terrain
eventually levelled out...

665
00:34:07,679 --> 00:34:11,750
which meant
we swapped terror
for extreme discomfort.

666
00:34:14,753 --> 00:34:17,789
Ah. Oh, God Almighty.

667
00:34:17,856 --> 00:34:20,792
I don't think these cars
were actually designed

668
00:34:20,859 --> 00:34:23,495
to take this much punishment.

669
00:34:23,562 --> 00:34:26,132
- And I know we weren't.
- (GROANS)

670
00:34:26,165 --> 00:34:27,833
The only thing is,

671
00:34:27,899 --> 00:34:31,603
James's car rides lower
than this and will be worse.

672
00:34:31,670 --> 00:34:34,606
Argh! Ow!

673
00:34:34,673 --> 00:34:36,408
Ow! Ow! Ow!

674
00:34:38,144 --> 00:34:40,312
Agh!

675
00:34:40,379 --> 00:34:42,414
JEREMY: Soon,
the relentless battering

676
00:34:42,481 --> 00:34:45,151
started to cause breakdowns.

677
00:34:45,184 --> 00:34:46,752
(ENGINE SPLUTTERS)

678
00:34:46,818 --> 00:34:49,921
Sand... Sand in gear shift.

679
00:34:49,988 --> 00:34:52,858
JEREMY: My throttle is
jammed wide open, people.

680
00:34:55,161 --> 00:34:58,230
(ENGINE REVS AND WHINES)

681
00:35:03,435 --> 00:35:06,438
The problem is that every
time the air filter, here,

682
00:35:06,505 --> 00:35:09,040
turns as I'm driving along--
which it does--

683
00:35:09,175 --> 00:35:11,177
it's jamming the throttle.

684
00:35:12,178 --> 00:35:13,379
(SIGHS)

685
00:35:14,480 --> 00:35:16,182
What's going on here?

686
00:35:17,783 --> 00:35:19,084
What's up?

687
00:35:19,185 --> 00:35:21,086
The throttle is now jamming

688
00:35:21,187 --> 00:35:22,688
fully open all the time.

689
00:35:22,754 --> 00:35:24,656
Oh, problem.

690
00:35:40,372 --> 00:35:42,608
(TAPPING AND CLANGING)

691
00:35:42,674 --> 00:35:43,775
Oh, God.

692
00:35:45,211 --> 00:35:49,448
It is still moving.
(GROANS)

693
00:35:49,515 --> 00:35:51,550
RICHARD: Many miles ahead,

694
00:35:51,617 --> 00:35:54,653
we'd pulled over for a break
from the endless bumps,

695
00:35:54,720 --> 00:35:57,689
and James was being
very interesting!

696
00:36:01,059 --> 00:36:04,062
The good thing about this hat
is you can angle it,
like a heliostat,

697
00:36:04,129 --> 00:36:05,431
to where
the sun's coming from.

698
00:36:05,497 --> 00:36:07,032
Yes, that's true.

699
00:36:07,098 --> 00:36:09,735
But you still look a tit.

700
00:36:09,801 --> 00:36:12,904
Luckily for Hammond, who
could do with the company,

701
00:36:12,971 --> 00:36:15,641
I was back on the move.

702
00:36:15,707 --> 00:36:19,978
Right, a new style of driving
is now required.

703
00:36:20,045 --> 00:36:24,082
This arm for steering,
this arm for changing gear,

704
00:36:24,149 --> 00:36:29,020
and then another arm
for deaccelerating, like so.

705
00:36:29,087 --> 00:36:31,022
Yes!

706
00:36:31,089 --> 00:36:32,724
Accelerate.

707
00:36:32,791 --> 00:36:34,626
(ENGINE REVS)

708
00:36:34,693 --> 00:36:36,528
Deaccelerate.

709
00:36:36,595 --> 00:36:38,997
Sometimes, if you
listen very carefully,

710
00:36:39,064 --> 00:36:40,832
you can hear my genius.

711
00:36:43,134 --> 00:36:45,070
JEREMY: Back as a threesome,
we continued

712
00:36:45,136 --> 00:36:49,541
with our seemingly
endless journey to the east.

713
00:36:49,608 --> 00:36:52,744
Just need to find a road now.
This is not funny any more.

714
00:36:52,811 --> 00:36:55,347
Enough desert.

715
00:36:55,414 --> 00:36:57,449
I don't want another night
in the desert.

716
00:36:58,817 --> 00:37:01,620
I smell pretty bad.

717
00:37:01,687 --> 00:37:03,389
And I suspect that
if we manage

718
00:37:03,455 --> 00:37:06,325
to find somewhere tonight
near civilisation,

719
00:37:06,392 --> 00:37:08,294
we should probably
have a ceremonial

720
00:37:08,360 --> 00:37:11,196
bonfire of the underpants.

721
00:37:11,297 --> 00:37:12,664
JAMES: In truth, though,

722
00:37:12,731 --> 00:37:15,767
I thought we'd be
in the desert forever.

723
00:37:15,834 --> 00:37:19,971
But then,
late in the afternoon...

724
00:37:20,038 --> 00:37:25,577
I'm looking ahead,
and I'm not seeing
an endless sea of sand.

725
00:37:26,478 --> 00:37:28,414
I'm seeing green.

726
00:37:29,948 --> 00:37:32,718
Trees!
Those are trees and shrubs!

727
00:37:37,623 --> 00:37:38,690
Pylons!

728
00:37:38,757 --> 00:37:41,327
Pylons!
That means electricity.

729
00:37:45,631 --> 00:37:46,798
Oh, yes!

730
00:37:47,966 --> 00:37:49,501
Civilisation!

731
00:37:51,403 --> 00:37:54,005
JAMES:
And then, best of all...

732
00:37:55,774 --> 00:37:56,942
Oh, my God.

733
00:38:05,116 --> 00:38:07,919
I honestly thought we had
another night of sleeping...

734
00:38:07,986 --> 00:38:09,555
- (JAMES SIGHS)
- ...in the sand.

735
00:38:09,621 --> 00:38:11,957
But, no! Look at it!

736
00:38:13,759 --> 00:38:15,761
Nicest thing I've ever seen.

737
00:38:19,365 --> 00:38:21,800
JEREMY: I could go east,
I could go west...

738
00:38:21,867 --> 00:38:24,202
Whichever way you go, it goes
somewhere. That's the point.

739
00:38:24,269 --> 00:38:26,037
It's a road,
it goes somewhere.

740
00:38:26,104 --> 00:38:29,240
You know what we've
just done, don't you?

741
00:38:29,375 --> 00:38:32,744
We've just crossed
the Namib Desert
in three beach buggies.

742
00:38:32,811 --> 00:38:34,145
- We have.
- We did.

743
00:38:34,212 --> 00:38:36,014
We did.

744
00:38:36,081 --> 00:38:38,950
There is literally nothing
can stop us now.

745
00:38:43,154 --> 00:38:44,756
JEREMY: Admittedly,

746
00:38:44,823 --> 00:38:48,059
our crossing had not exactly
been as the crow flies,

